## 6. Effects and functionalism

An essential part of a relation definition is the section labelled **Effect**. It contains a statement of some condition that is routinely achieved through the use of the relation .

* 
**Plausibility:** For each relation and schema definition, the definition applies only if it is plausible to the analyst that the writer wanted to use the spanned portion of the text to achieve the Effect.


* **Functional Account:** As a result, an RST analysis always constitutes a plausible account of what the writer wanted to achieve with each part of the text. An RST analysis is thus a functional account of the text as a whole .


* 
**Structure of Functions:** RST structures are structures of functions rather than structures of forms, because definitions are stated in terms of effects on the reader rather than linguistic forms (conjunctions, tense, etc.) .


7. Use and consequences of RST
Up to this point, the paper has been devoted to defining and exemplifying the conventions, methods and mechanisms of RST. Here we review some results of applying RST constructs to natural texts .

7.1. Results from text analysis

A key feature of the definitional sections is that they do not force texts to have RST structures. The fact that texts have such structures is a result in itself . Based on the analysis of hundreds of texts:

Universality: Virtually every text has an RST analysis.

Exceptions: Certain text types characteristically do not have RST analyses. These include laws, contracts, reports 'for the record' and various kinds of language-as-art, including some poetry .

Predominance: In our culture, texts that have RST analyses predominate. It is typical for texts to be hierarchically structured and functionally organized .

7.2. Results from studies of relational properties

The presence of structural relations in a text has consequences that closely resemble the consequences of clausal assertion. The text structure conveys propositions, called relational propositions .

Properties of relational assertions:

They are not necessarily clausally expressed.

They can be conveyed with no formal signal (conjunctions, etc.) at all .

One relational proposition arises from each relation of the RST structure .

They are essential to the coherence of their texts.

Recognizing the relations of a text is tantamount to recognizing its RST structure and the basis of its coherence. Relational propositions are not invited inferences or Gricean implicatures; they are as inevitable as text structure itself .
